2.4 Building baseline¶

In [45]:
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score, mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error

def mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred): 
    return np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / y_true)) * 100

models_scoring = pd.DataFrame({"Parameter":["R2", "MAE", "MSE", "MAPE"]})

def add_scoring(name, true_y, prediction_y, table=models_scoring):
    r2 = r2_score(true_y, prediction_y)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(true_y, prediction_y)
    mse = mean_squared_error(true_y, prediction_y)
    mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(true_y, prediction_y)
    table[name] = pd.Series([r2, mae, mse, mape])

def plot_predictions(pred, test=y_test, title='Prediction vs actual'):
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(test, "c", label="actual")
    plt.plot(pred, "r", label = "prediction")
    plt.legend(loc="best")
    plt.axis('tight')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.grid(True);

3.2 SARIMA¶

In [52]:
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf            # statistics and econometrics
import statsmodels.tsa.api as smt
import scipy.stats as scs

def tsplot(y, lags=None, figsize=(15, 10), style='bmh'):
    """
        Plot time series, its ACF and PACF, calculate Dickey–Fuller test
        
        y - timeseries
        lags - how many lags to include in ACF, PACF calculation
    """
    if not isinstance(y, pd.Series):
        y = pd.Series(y)
        
    with plt.style.context(style):    
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
        layout = (2, 2)
        ts_ax = plt.subplot2grid(layout, (0, 0), colspan=2)
        acf_ax = plt.subplot2grid(layout, (1, 0))
        pacf_ax = plt.subplot2grid(layout, (1, 1))
        
        y.plot(ax=ts_ax)
        p_value = sm.tsa.stattools.adfuller(y)[1]
        ts_ax.set_title('Time Series Analysis Plots\n Dickey-Fuller: p={0:.5f}'.format(p_value))
        smt.graphics.plot_acf(y, lags=lags, ax=acf_ax)
        smt.graphics.plot_pacf(y, lags=lags, ax=pacf_ax, method="ols")
        plt.tight_layout()

tsplot(y_train)

def plotCoefficients(model, threshhold=50):
    """
        Plots sorted coefficient values of the model
    """
    
    coefs = pd.DataFrame(model.coef_, X_train.columns)
    coefs.columns = ["coef"]
    coefs["abs"] = coefs.coef.apply(np.abs)
    coefs = coefs.sort_values(by="abs", ascending=False).drop(["abs"], axis=1)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 7))
    coefs[abs(coefs.coef)>threshhold].coef.plot(kind='bar')
    plt.grid(True, axis='y')
    plt.hlines(y=0, xmin=0, xmax=len(coefs), linestyles='dashed');

plotCoefficients(lr)

from hyperopt import hp, tpe
from hyperopt.fmin import fmin

def objective(params):
    params = {'n_estimators': int(params['n_estimators']), 'max_depth': int(params['max_depth']),
             'subsample': float(params['subsample'])}
    clf = GradientBoostingRegressor(**params)
    clf.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
#     score = cross_val_score(clf, X, y, scoring='f1').mean()
    y_pred = pd.Series(clf.predict(X_test_scaled), index=y_test.index)
    score = mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_test, y_pred)
    print("F1 {:.3f} params {}".format(score, params))
    return score

space = {
    'n_estimators': hp.quniform('n_estimators', 50, 500, 25),
    'max_depth': hp.quniform('max_depth', 1, 10, 1),
    'subsample': hp.quniform('subsample', 0.1, 1, 0.1),  
}


best = fmin(fn=objective,
            space=space,
            algo=tpe.suggest,
            max_evals=50)

4. Conclusion¶

Добиться точности прогноза, сравнимой с простейшим средним по часам+дням недели удалось только с применением градиентного бустинга. Таким образом можно сделать вывод, что для решения данной задачи достаточно пользоваться базовым прогнозом, который не требует высоких вычислительных мощностей и частого переобучения.
